I"¡(<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>

<p>Problem-solving is a vital skill in mathematics and beyond, touching every field where critical thinking and innovation are necessary. Paul Zeitz‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Art and Craft of Problem Solving‚Äù offers a rich compendium of strategies and insights that are as practical as they are enlightening. This book delves into the mindset and methodologies that can turn a perplexing problem into a solvable challenge. Here, we explore key strategies from Zeitz‚Äôs work, providing a roadmap for anyone looking to sharpen their problem-solving abilities.</p>

<h2 id="strategies-for-getting-started">Strategies for Getting started</h2>

<p>As I said before, most Putnam problems, you won‚Äôt even know how to start working on them. Thus, having strategies to just do that is very important.</p>

<h4 id="orientation-starting-off-right">Orientation: Starting Off Right</h4>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>A crucial aspect of problem-solving that Zeitz highlights is the orientation phase. Here are some essential steps to take at the beginning of every problem:</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Read the problem carefully. Pay attention to details such as positive vs. negative, finite vs. infinite, and so on. The nuances in the problem statement can significantly impact your approach.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Begin to classify the problem. Is it a ‚Äúto find‚Äù or ‚Äúto prove‚Äù problem? Is the problem similar to others you have encountered before? Classifying the problem can guide your initial steps and help in choosing the right strategy.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Identify the hypothesis and conclusion. Clearly distinguish between what is given (the hypothesis) and what needs to be shown or found (the conclusion).</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Preliminary brainstorming. Start with some quick, preliminary brainstorming to set the stage for deeper analysis:</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<blockquote>
  <ol>
    <li>Think about convenient notation that can simplify your work.</li>
    <li>Consider if a particular method of argument might be plausible.</li>
    <li>Try to guess a possible solution, trusting your intuition.</li>
    <li>Look for key words or concepts that might be important, such as prime numbers, perfect squares, or infinite sequences.</li>
  </ol>
</blockquote>

<p>Once you‚Äôve completed these steps, take a moment to review and repeat them. Rereading the problem and rethinking your initial classification, hypothesis, and conclusion can often lead to new insights and a clearer understanding.</p>

<h4 id="get-your-hands-dirty">Get your hands dirty</h4>

<p>Zeitz encourages a hands-on approach to problem-solving. Stay loose and experiment‚Äîplug in numbers, test out different scenarios, and look for patterns. This playful, exploratory phase is not only fun but also essential. Many high-level mathematical discoveries start with simple ‚Äúplug and chug‚Äù methods. By staying flexible and open to experimentation, you can uncover unexpected insights and build a deeper understanding of the problem at hand.</p>

<h4 id="penultimate-step">Penultimate step</h4>

<p>Once you know what the desired conclusion is, think about what might yield that conclusion in a single step. Sometimes, identifying this penultimate step can make the final solution more obvious. For instance, if you need to prove that two complex expressions are equal, consider showing separately that each is less than or equal to the other. Or, if you need to prove that one expression is always even and another is always odd, focus on these properties as a penultimate step. Even if the search for a penultimate step doesn‚Äôt yield an immediate solution, it can help you refine your overall proof strategy.</p>

<h4 id="wishful-thinking-and-make-it-easier">Wishful thinking and Make it easier</h4>

<p>Combining psychology and mathematics, these strategies help break initial impasses. Ask yourself, ‚ÄúWhat is it about the problem that makes it hard?‚Äù Then, temporarily remove that difficulty. Simplify big, ugly numbers, or remove complicated algebraic terms. This wishful thinking can lead to bold solutions or at least highlight the core difficulty, making it easier to address. By making the problem more approachable, you can boost your confidence and have more fun with the process.</p>

<h2 id="methods-of-argument">Methods of argument</h2>

<h4 id="argument-by-contradiction">Argument by contradiction</h4>

<h6 id="example">Example</h6>

<p>Prove that if $p$ is prime, then modulo $p$, every non-zero number has a unique multiplicative inverse; i.e., if $x$ is not a multiple of $p$, then there is a unique $y \in \{1,2,3,‚Ä¶,p-1\}$ such that $xy \equiv 1 (\mod p).$ For example, if $p = 7$, the multiplicative inverses $(\mod 7)$ of $1,2,3,4,5,6$ are $1,4,5,2,3,6$ respectively.</p>

<h6 id="proof">Proof</h6>

<p>Also mention direct proofs!!!</p>

<h4 id="mathematical-induction">Mathematical induction</h4>

<h5 id="standard-induction">Standard Induction</h5>

<p>Let $S$ be a subset of the set of natural numbers $\mathbb{N}.$ If</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>$S$ contains $1$ and</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>$S$ contains the positive intenger  $n + 1$ whenever $S$ contains $n,$</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>then $S = \mathbb{N}.$</p>

<p>In essence, the Principle of Mathematical Induction tells us that if we have a set $S \subseteq \mathbb{N}$ containing $1$ and if $S$ contains the integer $n + 1$ whenever $S$ contains $n,$ then $S$ must contain $1 + 1 = 2.$ But then $S$ must also contain $2 + 1 = 3,$ and $3 + 1 = 4,$ and so on. Therefore, $S$ will contain all natural numbers.</p>

<h6 id="example-1">Example</h6>

<p>Apply the Principle of Mathematical Induction to establish equation $1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + ‚Ä¶ + 2^{n-1} = 2^n - 1.$</p>

<h6 id="solution">Solution</h6>

<p>Let $S = \{ n \in \mathbb{N} : 1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + ‚Ä¶ + 2^{n-1} = 2^n - 1 \}.$ To use the Principle of Mathematical Induction, we need to show that $1 \in S$ and that $n+1 \in S$ whenever $n \in S.$ First, we will show that $1 \in S$(the base case.) Notice that when $n = 1,$ we have</p>

\[1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + ... + 2^{n-1} = 2^0 = 1\]

<p>and</p>

\[2^n - 1 = 2^1 - 1 = 2 - 1 = 1.\]

<p>So the equation is true when $n = 1,$ which means that $1 \in S.$ For the inductive step, we need to show that $n+1 \in S$ whenever $n \in S.$ To do so, we will assume that $n \in S$ for some integer $n &gt; 1$(the inductive hypothesis.) In this case, we will assume that</p>

\[\begin{align}
1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + ... + 2^{n-1} = 2^n - 1.
\end{align}\]

<p>We then need to prove that $n+1 \in S.$ So we need to show that</p>

\[1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + ... + 2^{n-1} + 2^{(n+1) - 1} = 2^{n+1} - 1\]

<p>or, equivalently,</p>

\[\begin{align}
1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + ... + 2^{n-1} + 2^{n} = 2^{n+1} - 1.
\end{align}\]

<p>To prove ($2$), we can substitute from ($1$) in the left hand side of ($2$) to obtain</p>

\[1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + ... + 2^{n-1} + 2^{n} = (1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + ... + 2^{n-1}) + 2^{n}\]

\[= (2^n - 1) + 2^n\]

\[= 2(2^n) - 1\]

\[= 2^{n+1} - 1\]

<p>which shows that $n+1 \in S.$ Therefore, $S = \mathbb{N}$ by the Principle of Mathematical Induction.</p>

